ate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal proto-metabolic generation of pyruvate from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization-linked reducing conditions; based on hydrothermal CO2 fixation context cited in the review for pyruvate availability\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-promoted CO2 reduction and C-C bond construction under hydrothermal reducing conditions generate pyruvate as an upstream C3 keto-acid feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is identified in the literature review as a hydrothermal precursor available from CO2 + H2 fixation on native iron minerals at about 100 degrees C, supporting its role as an upstream input to the glutamate network; this node is included strictly to connect the reported glutamate network to simple feedstocks and is therefore a literature-grounded connector rather than a glutamate-specific transformation (Preiner et al., 2020, as summarized in the curated review; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface generation of glyoxylate under photochemical/cyanosulfidic conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral mediated cyanosulfidic/photochemical surface chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed surface pools; connector step included because the review states glyoxylate can arise from UV photochemistry and cyanosulfidic chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven redox chemistry on mineral surfaces converts simple C1/CN feedstocks into oxidized C2 carbonyl species including glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The curated review states that glyoxylate is produced by UV photochemistry and cyanosulfidic surface chemistry and can then feed hydrothermal aldol chemistry with pyruvate. The exact glutamate-focused paper for this upstream production is not specified in detail in the review, so this connecting step is conservative and literature-guided rather than newly invented. It preserves the documented environmental interconnection Surface to Hydrothermal emphasized in the review (Ritson, 2021; Springsteen et al., 2018, as summarized in the curated review).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe2+-catalyzed aldol condensation of pyruvate and glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrothermal aqueous conditions at 70 degrees C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe2+-assisted aldol condensation joins the enolizable C3 pyruvate donor to the aldehydic carbonyl of glyoxylate to form the C5 alpha-keto acid 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is directly documented as the first step of the iron-promoted route from pyruvate plus glyoxylate to glutamate under hydrothermal conditions at 70 degrees C. The cited studies demonstrate formation of 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate and establish this as a core protometabolic C-C bond-forming step (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Springsteen et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe2+-promoted dehydration of 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrothermal aqueous conditions at 70 degrees C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Beta-elimination removes water from 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate to generate the conjugated unsaturated dicarboxylic keto-acid 4-oxopent-2-enedioate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This dehydration step is directly reported in the hydrothermal iron-promoted network to glutamate and is part of the continuous sequence operating at 70 degrees C in water (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe2+-promoted reduction of 4-oxopent-2-enedioate to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly reducing hydrothermal conditions at 70 degrees C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iron-mediated hydrogenation/reduction of the C=C bond in the unsaturated intermediate affords saturated 2-oxoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the third experimentally demonstrated step of the iron-driven pathway to 2-oxoglutarate and ultimately glutamate under hydrothermal conditions (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Iron-promoted reductive amination of 2-oxoglutarate with hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0) and ferrous iron (Fe2+)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"70 degrees C hydrothermal water; hydroxylamine as nitrogen donor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydroxylamine reacts with the alpha-keto group of 2-oxoglutarate, followed by iron-mediated reduction of the imine/oxime-like intermediate to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The curated review identifies this as the final step of the Muchowska iron-promoted hydrothermal pathway and notes hydroxylamine as the nitrogen donor with Fe0/Fe2+ supplying reducing power. It is experimentally demonstrated at 70 degrees C in water (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"FeS-catalyzed reductive amination of 2-oxoglutarate with ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"hydrothermal vent conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferrous sulfide (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation; ammonia as direct nitrogen source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"FeS surface catalyzes imine formation between 2-oxoglutarate and ammonia and promotes subsequent reduction to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This direct hydrothermal route from 2-oxoglutarate plus ammonia to glutamate is explicitly demonstrated on FeS under alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions and is a key alternative to the hydroxylamine-dependent route (Kitadai et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of 2-hydroxypentanedinitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface cyanosulfidic mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool/cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia displaces the hydroxyl-bearing functionality in the dinitrile precursor to generate the corresponding aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the first reported step of the Patel-Sutherland glutamate route in cyanosulfidic protometabolism, converting 2-hydroxypentanedinitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile in aqueous surface settings (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to L-glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface aqueous mineral matrix\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sequential hydrolysis of both nitriles in evaporitic/cyanosulfidic settings; water in excess\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Both nitrile groups undergo stepwise hydration to amides and then carboxylic acids, yielding glutamate and releasing ammonia.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final dinitrile hydrolysis step is directly reported for glutamate formation in the unified cyanosulfidic chemistry of Patel and co-workers and provides a fully surface-based route to the target (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal oxidation of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"hydrothermal\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"hydrothermal iron-bearing fluid/mineral system\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"oxidative dehydrogenation in hydrothermal fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-hydroxy group is dehydrogenated to the alpha-keto state, producing 2-oxoglutarate and molecular hydrogen.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Lee and co-workers showed that 2-hydroxyglutaric acid can be oxidized to 2-oxoglutarate with release of H2 in hydrothermal fluids, establishing an alternate hydrothermal feeder route to the central hub (Lee et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic oxidation of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"surface ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanosulfidic sulfur-bearing surface mineral setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"surface cyanosulfidic oxidation as part of a prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface redox chemistry oxidizes the alpha-hydroxy acid to the corresponding alpha-keto acid 2-oxoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson reported a cyanosulfidic surface route in which 2-hydroxyglutarate is oxidized to 2-oxoglutarate, complementing the hydrothermal route and providing documented Surface to Hydrothermal network interconnection via the central keto-acid hub (Ritson, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal decomposition of 2-amino-4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanedioic acid to 2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"hydrothermal\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"hydrothermal iron-bearing mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"retro-aldol/deamination behavior in hydrothermal fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex amino acid derivative undergoes decomposition involving retro-aldol cleavage and oxidative deamination to yield 2-oxoglutarate and ammonia.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Lee et al. identified 2-amino-4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanedioic acid as a hydrothermal precursor that decomposes to 2-oxoglutarate plus ammonia, adding another experimentally grounded entry route into the central glutamate hub (Lee et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface decarboxylation of 3-oxalomalic acid to 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"296 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ambient aqueous surface mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"about 3 hours; oxidative decarboxylation in linked glyoxylate cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"3-Oxalomalic acid loses CO2 from its oxalyl-derived portion to furnish the C5 intermediate 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Springsteen and co-workers experimentally demonstrated this ambient-temperature route to 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate as part of linked glyoxylate cycles, making it a crucial surface feeder into the hydrothermal iron network (Springsteen et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Transfer of glutamate into the biochemical amino-acid pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool accumulation and concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Physical accumulation and partitioning of glutamate into a concentrated prebiotic amino-acid pool suitable for downstream assembly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The curated review states that glutamate produced by hydrothermal or surface routes enters the prebiotic amino acid pool and serves as a nitrogen carrier and assembly precursor. This is a necessary connection from synthesis to biochemical utilization and is explicitly motivated by the review's environmental interconnection section; it is a network-assembly step rather than a new chemical transformation (Muchowska et al., 2019; Patel et al., 2015; Kitadai et al., 2019; curated review synthesis).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic peptide bond formation from glutamate pool to diglutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation between two glutamate molecules during dehydration cycles forms a peptide bond and releases water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The instructions require downstream biochemical assembly, and the curated review explicitly notes that glutamate feeds peptide bond formation and proto-metabolic assembly. This step is therefore included as a plausible prebiotic utilization node rather than an experimentally demonstrated glutamate-synthesis step; it is necessarily more general and should be regarded as a network connector built on established prebiotic peptide condensation concepts (curated review synthesis; generally consistent with prebiotic wet-dry peptide literature).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal iron route with hydroxylamine amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate and surface-fed glyoxylate converge in the Muchowska iron network to form 2-oxoglutarate, then glutamate via hydroxylamine reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical hydrothermal iron route with FeS/ammonia amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Same upstream aldol-dehydration-reduction sequence, but final glutamate formation occurs on FeS with ammonia under alkaline hydrothermal conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface 3-oxalomalate feeder into hydrothermal hydroxylamine amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Ambient surface decarboxylation forms 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate, which enters the hydrothermal iron sequence and ends with hydroxylamine amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface 3-oxalomalate feeder into hydrothermal FeS/ammonia amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface-generated 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate is transported into hydrothermal chemistry, then converted to glutamate through FeS-catalyzed reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct surface dinitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry converts 2-hydroxypentanedinitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile and then hydrolyzes it to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal 2-hydroxyglutarate route with hydroxylamine\",\n      \"description\": \"2-Hydroxyglutarate is oxidized in hydrothermal fluids to 2-oxoglutarate, then aminated with hydroxylamine in the iron system.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal 2-hydroxyglutarate route with FeS/ammonia\",\n      \"description\": \"2-Hydroxyglutarate feeds the central keto-acid hub in hydrothermal systems, then glutamate forms via FeS-catalyzed reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic 2-hydroxyglutarate oxidation plus hydroxylamine amination\",\n      \"description\": \"A surface route generates 2-oxoglutarate from 2-hydroxyglutarate, which then enters hydrothermal iron-mediated hydroxylamine amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic 2-hydroxyglutarate oxidation plus FeS/ammonia amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface-produced 2-oxoglutarate is delivered into hydrothermal vent chemistry and converted directly to glutamate on FeS.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal decomposition route from amino-hydroxy-methylpentanedioate\",\n      \"description\": \"Complex hydrothermal precursor decomposes to 2-oxoglutarate, then glutamate is formed by direct FeS-catalyzed amination with ammonia.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Glutamate", "overall_strategy": "This network centers on 2-oxoglutarate as the dominant hub connecting hydrothermal iron-driven protometabolism and surface cyanosulfidic chemistry to glutamate formation. Hydrothermal routes follow the experimentally demonstrated Fe2+-catalyzed sequence from pyruvate and glyoxylate through 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate and 4-oxopent-2-enedioate to 2-oxoglutarate, then to glutamate by either Fe0/Fe2+-promoted reductive amination with hydroxylamine or FeS-catalyzed reductive amination with ammonia. Surface routes follow the Patel-Sutherland dinitrile pathway directly to glutamate and the Ritson/Springsteen routes that generate hydrothermal intermediates or 2-oxoglutarate under ambient cyanosulfidic conditions. The resulting glutamate pool then feeds biochemical/prebiotic peptide assembly. Ten valid target-reaching pathways are enumerated as distinct route combinations through this connected bipartite graph.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H6O6", "iupac_name": "4-hydroxy-2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O6/c6-2(4(8)9)1-3(7)5(10)11/h2,6H,1H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H4O5", "iupac_name": "4-oxopent-2-enedioic acid", "common_name": "4-oxopent-2-enedioic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H4O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "2-oxoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "H3NO", "iupac_name": "hydroxylamine", "common_name": "hydroxylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3NO/c1-2/h2H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "L-glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypentanedinitrile", "common_name": "2-hydroxypentanedinitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O/c6-3-1-2-5(8)4-7/h5,8H,1-2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedinitrile", "common_name": "2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7N3/c6-3-1-2-5(8)4-7/h5H,1-2,8H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H8O5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypentanedioic acid", "common_name": "2-hydroxyglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3,6H,1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H11NO5", "iupac_name": "2-amino-4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanedioic acid", "common_name": "2-amino-4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanedioic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H11NO5/c1-6(12,5(10)11)2-3(7)4(8)9/h3,12H,2,7H2,1H3,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C6H6O8", "iupac_name": "3-oxalomalic acid", "common_name": "3-oxalomalic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6O8/c7-2(5(11)12)1(4(9)10)3(8)6(13)14/h1-2,7H,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)(H,13,14)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H16N2O6", "iupac_name": "L-glutamic acid", "common_name": "glutamate in peptide assembly pool", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C10H16N2O7", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-amino-4-carboxybutanoyl)amino]pentanedioic acid", "common_name": "diglutamate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal proto-metabolic generation of pyruvate from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373 K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "serpentinization-linked reducing conditions; based on hydrothermal CO2 fixation context cited in the review for pyruvate availability"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-promoted CO2 reduction and C-C bond construction under hydrothermal reducing conditions generate pyruvate as an upstream C3 keto-acid feedstock.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is identified in the literature review as a hydrothermal precursor available from CO2 + H2 fixation on native iron minerals at about 100 degrees C, supporting its role as an upstream input to the glutamate network; this node is included strictly to connect the reported glutamate network to simple feedstocks and is therefore a literature-grounded connector rather than a glutamate-specific transformation (Preiner et al., 2020, as summarized in the curated review; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface generation of glyoxylate under photochemical/cyanosulfidic conditions", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral mediated cyanosulfidic/photochemical surface chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed surface pools; connector step included because the review states glyoxylate can arise from UV photochemistry and cyanosulfidic chemistry"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven redox chemistry on mineral surfaces converts simple C1/CN feedstocks into oxidized C2 carbonyl species including glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "The curated review states that glyoxylate is produced by UV photochemistry and cyanosulfidic surface chemistry and can then feed hydrothermal aldol chemistry with pyruvate. The exact glutamate-focused paper for this upstream production is not specified in detail in the review, so this connecting step is conservative and literature-guided rather than newly invented. It preserves the documented environmental interconnection Surface to Hydrothermal emphasized in the review (Ritson, 2021; Springsteen et al., 2018, as summarized in the curated review)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fe2+-catalyzed aldol condensation of pyruvate and glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343 K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydrothermal aqueous conditions at 70 degrees C"}, "mechanism": "Fe2+-assisted aldol condensation joins the enolizable C3 pyruvate donor to the aldehydic carbonyl of glyoxylate to form the C5 alpha-keto acid 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate.", "reasoning": "This reaction is directly documented as the first step of the iron-promoted route from pyruvate plus glyoxylate to glutamate under hydrothermal conditions at 70 degrees C. The cited studies demonstrate formation of 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate and establish this as a core protometabolic C-C bond-forming step (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Springsteen et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Fe2+-promoted dehydration of 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343 K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydrothermal aqueous conditions at 70 degrees C"}, "mechanism": "Beta-elimination removes water from 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate to generate the conjugated unsaturated dicarboxylic keto-acid 4-oxopent-2-enedioate.", "reasoning": "This dehydration step is directly reported in the hydrothermal iron-promoted network to glutamate and is part of the continuous sequence operating at 70 degrees C in water (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Fe2+-promoted reduction of 4-oxopent-2-enedioate to 2-oxoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343 K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly reducing hydrothermal conditions at 70 degrees C"}, "mechanism": "Iron-mediated hydrogenation/reduction of the C=C bond in the unsaturated intermediate affords saturated 2-oxoglutarate.", "reasoning": "This is the third experimentally demonstrated step of the iron-driven pathway to 2-oxoglutarate and ultimately glutamate under hydrothermal conditions (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Iron-promoted reductive amination of 2-oxoglutarate with hydroxylamine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "ferrous iron (Fe2+)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343 K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0) and ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "70 degrees C hydrothermal water; hydroxylamine as nitrogen donor"}, "mechanism": "Hydroxylamine reacts with the alpha-keto group of 2-oxoglutarate, followed by iron-mediated reduction of the imine/oxime-like intermediate to glutamate.", "reasoning": "The curated review identifies this as the final step of the Muchowska iron-promoted hydrothermal pathway and notes hydroxylamine as the nitrogen donor with Fe0/Fe2+ supplying reducing power. It is experimentally demonstrated at 70 degrees C in water (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "FeS-catalyzed reductive amination of 2-oxoglutarate with ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "hydrothermal vent conditions", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "ferrous sulfide (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation; ammonia as direct nitrogen source"}, "mechanism": "FeS surface catalyzes imine formation between 2-oxoglutarate and ammonia and promotes subsequent reduction to glutamate.", "reasoning": "This direct hydrothermal route from 2-oxoglutarate plus ammonia to glutamate is explicitly demonstrated on FeS under alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions and is a key alternative to the hydroxylamine-dependent route (Kitadai et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Amination of 2-hydroxypentanedinitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface cyanosulfidic mineral environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool/cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia displaces the hydroxyl-bearing functionality in the dinitrile precursor to generate the corresponding aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the first reported step of the Patel-Sutherland glutamate route in cyanosulfidic protometabolism, converting 2-hydroxypentanedinitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile in aqueous surface settings (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to L-glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface aqueous mineral matrix", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sequential hydrolysis of both nitriles in evapor