into the biochemical amino-acid pool", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool accumulation and concentration"}, "mechanism": "Physical accumulation and partitioning of glutamate into a concentrated prebiotic amino-acid pool suitable for downstream assembly.", "reasoning": "The curated review states that glutamate produced by hydrothermal or surface routes enters the prebiotic amino acid pool and serves as a nitrogen carrier and assembly precursor. This is a necessary connection from synthesis to biochemical utilization and is explicitly motivated by the review's environmental interconnection section; it is a network-assembly step rather than a new chemical transformation (Muchowska et al., 2019; Patel et al., 2015; Kitadai et al., 2019; curated review synthesis)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Prebiotic peptide bond formation from glutamate pool to diglutamate", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_002"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Condensation between two glutamate molecules during dehydration cycles forms a peptide bond and releases water.", "reasoning": "The instructions require downstream biochemical assembly, and the curated review explicitly notes that glutamate feeds peptide bond formation and proto-metabolic assembly. This step is therefore included as a plausible prebiotic utilization node rather than an experimentally demonstrated glutamate-synthesis step; it is necessarily more general and should be regarded as a network connector built on established prebiotic peptide condensation concepts (curated review synthesis; generally consistent with prebiotic wet-dry peptide li